<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Dr Katharina Dehnen-Schmutz, University of Coventry</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Dr Katharina </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Dehnen-Schmutz</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">, </span><br /><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">University of Coventry</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">I am an ecologist and have worked on invasive species, in particular plant invasions resulting from ornamental horticulture, for several years in different research projects at the Universities of York, Warwick and Coventry. I am sending this comment, as some of the specific questions the committee wants to address have been part of my research.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">In particular, I would like to comment on the first point of reference (“</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The principal drivers of the rising number of invasive species”) in relation to point </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">4 (“</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">list of harmful species to tackle, rather than a list of safe species which would not be restricted”).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The major active pathway for the introduction of invasive plants is ornamental horticulture. Most of the problematic invasive plants in Britain have been introduced as ornamental plants and later spread outside gardens. Currently, there are more than 75,000 plants available for sale in Britain according to the 2013 edition of the Royal Horticultural Society’s “Plant Finder” – in the first edition, published in 1987 just 22,000 plants were listed. These figures include many cultivars, not just species, but still give an indication of the scale of the numbers as well as the increase over just 16 years. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">This still on-going increase in the number of different plants cultivated is of particular concern as plants often take a long time from their first introduction to the point where they are first found to be growing outside cultivation. For plants introduced into Britain since the year 1500 this period is on average 125 years. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">An approach listing just 50 harmful species may give the impression that non-listed non-native species are safe to use. However, given the long period it may take to reveal the invasiveness of a plant, this may result in the large scale planting of potential future invaders, contributing significantly to their potential harmful impact in the future. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">I therefore suggest a “green list” approach for plants that are proven to be safer to use because they have been cultivated in Britain for over 125 years and have been widely planted. Green listed species would be recommend for planting in particular in areas close to nature reserves, in large landscaping projects or along infrastructure developments. It would not restrict the use of other non-listed plants in gardens and urban areas but provide an easy to achieve precaution against the potential impacts of future invasive plants.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The green list would complement the proposed list of harmful species, which should not be restricted to 50 species. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Re</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">ferences:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">Dehnen-Schmutz, K. (2011): Determining non-invasiveness in ornamental plants to build green lists. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Journal of Applied Ecology</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> 48: 1374-1380. </span><a href="http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1365-2664.2011.02061.x/full"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1365-2664.2011.02061.x/full</span></a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">Dehnen-Schmutz, K., Touza, J., Perrings, C. &amp; Williamson, M. (2007): A century of the ornamental plant trade and its impact on invasion success. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Diversity and Distributions</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">13</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">: 527-534.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><a href="http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1472-4642.2007.00359.x/abstract?deniedAccessCustomisedMessage=&amp;userIsAuthenticated=false"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1472-4642.2007.00359.x/abstract?deniedAccessCustomisedMessage=&amp;userIsAuthenticated=false</span></a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">Dehnen-Schmutz, K., Touza, J., Perrings, C. &amp; Williamson, M. (2007): The horticultural trade and ornamental plant invasions in Britain.  </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Conservation Biology</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">21</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">: 224-231. </span><a href="http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1523-1739.2006.00538.x/abstract?deniedAccessCustomisedMessage=&amp;userIsAuthenticated=false"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1523-1739.2006.00538.x/abstract?deniedAccessCustomisedMessage=&amp;userIsAuthenticated=false</span></a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">13 January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>